Make a file, look inside one.

Let's start with two verbs: making a file, and looking inside one.

To make an empty file, use touch, followed by a name. Touch was originally built to update a file's timestamps, and it still does that, but its side effect of creating a file when none exists is what you'll use it for most. It takes several names at once, so you can create three empty files in a single command.

To make a directory, use mkdir. Add the dash-p flag, for parents, and it creates a whole chain of nested directories in one step, and it also stays quiet if the directory already exists, which makes it safe in scripts.

Two things that catch newcomers. Linux filenames are case-sensitive: capital-R Report and lowercase report are two different files. And spaces in names need quoting; the convention is to just avoid them and use dashes or underscores instead.

Now, viewing. Pick the right tool for the size of the file. Cat dumps the whole file to your terminal. That's great for a small file and painful for a fifty-thousand-line log. The name is short for concatenate, because cat of two files prints them glued together.

For anything large, use less, an interactive pager. The clever part is that less doesn't load the whole file into memory, just the part you're looking at, so it opens a ten-gigabyte log instantly. Inside less: Space or b to page forward and back, slash then a pattern to search, n for the next match, g and capital-G for the start and end, and q to quit.

Head and tail print the first or last ten lines of a file; dash-n with a number changes the count. The star feature is tail dash-f, follow mode, which keeps printing new lines as they're appended. That's the standard way to watch a log file live: tail dash-f on slash-var-log-syslog.

One last tool, for identifying rather than reading. The file command reads the first few bytes of a file and tells you what it actually is: file on slash-bin-ls says "ELF executable"; file on a text file says "ASCII text." Linux doesn't trust file extensions, so this is how you find out what something really is.
